8. trahunt, ‘ spin.’ honestae, probably ‘ well—born,’ the dignity of the patron being enhanced by the respectability of his clients.

The purpurae seem to have been purple togas. It is clear that such things were worn, for Augustus as early as 13.c. 36 (Dion Cassius XLIX. 16) issued a decree that none but magistrates and senators should wear them. It is possible, however, that the purpurae are only the fringe of the toga praetexta, worn by all curule magistrates.
